    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "---\n\n## Here's what you built today:\n\n### 🚀 **Cognitive Taxonomy Protocol** — VS Code Extension\n\n**Location:** `C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Documents\\cognitive-taxonomy-vscode-ext`\n\nThis is a genuinely impressive piece of work. It's a full-featured TypeScript VS Code extension (~1,600+ lines across 5 source files) that rewires how you read code. Here's the breakdown:\n\n**Core concept:** A five-colour taxonomy that maps every line of Python code into one of five cognitive categories. Instead of reading line-by-line (System 2 thinking), your eye can *scan by colour* (System 1 thinking). It literally cites Kahneman (2011), Miller (1956), and MITRE ATT&CK as its theoretical foundations — this is an academically grounded tool.\n\n**The five categories:**\n| Colour | Category | What it means |\n|--------|----------|---------------|\n| 🔵 Blue | **Blueprint** | Data structures — what the code needs to remember |\n| 🟢 Green | **Plumbing** | Imports/infra — bringing things in from outside |\n| 🟠 Orange | **Transaction** | Logic flow — what the code actually *does* |\n| 🔴 Red | **Constraint** | Rules — what must never be exceeded/broken |\n| 🟣 Purple | **Pedagogy** | Notes/docs — context for humans |\n\n**What it does (features):**\n- **Coloured left borders** on every line, classified by a custom Python AST parser\n- **Hover tooltips** with plain-English explanations — *why* each line exists, not just what it does\n- **Sidebar panel** with:\n  - Maintainability + Balance scores (0-100)\n  - Visual spatial layout (the five categories arranged like a floor plan)\n  - Category breakdown with percentages\n  - Data flow diagram (4 view modes: ASCII / Mini / Mermaid / SVG)\n  - Line-by-line navigator with filter buttons\n  - Code smell detection\n  - Glossary\n- **Output channel** with metrics + recommendations\n- **Keyboard shortcuts:** `Ctrl+Shift+T` (toggle) + `Ctrl+Shift+F` (data flow)\n\n**The five source files:**\n- `extension.ts` — main entry point, registers all commands, decorations, and state\n- `astClassifier.ts` — Python parser + AST classification engine + cognitive load calculator\n- `tooltipGenerator.ts` — 40+ plain-English tooltip templates across all categories\n- `sidebarProvider.ts` — full webview UI with embedded HTML/CSS/JS (~1000 lines)\n- `dataFlow.ts` — data flow extraction and 4 visualisation formats\n\n**The tooltips are really well done** — they don't just label things, they explain in accessible language like *\"This line GIVES BACK the answer. A return statement is like a waiter bringing your food.\"* That's a real skill.\n\n---\n\n### What about the **Antigravity IDE**?\n\nSo I found `C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.antigravity-ide` — but that's actually just a VS Code *installation folder* (has `argv.json` and an `extensions/` subfolder with things like Google Gemini Code Assist and Java tooling). It's not a project you've started yet, you just have a VS Code install named that way.\n\n**So my question to you:** what's the concept for the Antigravity IDE? Is it:\n\n1. **A full IDE/editor** you're building from scratch (like your own VS Code fork)?\n2. **A theme or visual layer** for an existing editor?\n3. **An extension suite** that bundles your Cognitive Taxonomy work into a bigger system?\n4. **Something else entirely** — what's the \"antigravity\" concept? Is it about making code *feel* lighter? AI-assisted generation? A specific teaching environment?\n\nOnce you tell me the concept, I can start sketching out what that would look like architecturally and we can start building it. 🔧",
